  <h1>Olivia H. Scharfman</h1>

  <p>I have lately been spending time at the intersection of biotechnology
  and artificial intelligence, looking at designing systems that can
  understand, model, and defend life. I do private consulting, such as
  strategy and scientific policy work for biodefense as well as advising
  new companies on fundraising. I also do volunteer computational oncology
  work at Mount Sinai.</p>

  <p>Previously, I co-founded LincSwitch Therapeutics, where I helped build
  the founding R&amp;D team and led operations for the programmable lncRNA
  therapeutics platform (2&ndash;7 FTEs, 0&ndash;4 provisional patents).
  Before that, I was a Principal at <a href="https://salt.org">The SALT
  Fund</a>, investing in biology and deep tech startups such as <a
  href="https://generalbiological.com/">General Biological</a> and <a
  href="https://www.northwoodspace.io/">Northwood Space</a>.</p>

  <p>I have a B.S. in Molecular Biophysics and Biochemistry from Yale,
  where I researched lncRNA&rsquo;s role in aging and epigenetics, as well
  as the <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40324540/">role of aging
  and epigenetics in liver metabolism</a>, at the Department of Pathology.
  Earlier work included improving neural networks at DEKA Research &amp;
  Development, research for <a href="https://www.xprize.org/">XPRIZE</a>,
  and chairing the Board of Directors for <a href="https://seds.org/">SEDS-USA</a>
  (Students for the Exploration and Development of Space), a 501(c)3
  promoting student interest in space exploration.</p>
</Base>
